Mini-Project 2

Loading the data

Interpreting election data can be a daunting task, but necessary for maintaining an informed voting populace in a vibrant democracy. For this project, we imported U.S. Congressional data and candidate contribution data and combined interesting information from both data sets. We set out to find and interpret relationships between a congressional candidates incumbency status (incumbent or not) and the monetary funds for and against them as predictors of weather they won the election or not. Our data intent to show some of the complications in elections. We would like to shed insights into the following inquiries: Which state has more incumbent candidate? Do incumbent candidates have a higher chance of securing funding? Do the amount of funding help a candidate to win?

We wrote a function that allows us to interpret the data via a stacked bar graph for any state. In every state, there are certain candidates who receive more contribution than others. The data intent to show that the amount of contribution is correlated with whether the candidate is facing a competitive opponent.

Transaction Type Key:

24A -> Independent expenditure opposing election of candidate AGAINST 24E -> Independent expenditure advocating election of candidate FOR 24F -> Communication cost for candidate (only for Form 7 filer) FOR 24N -> Communication cost against candidate (only for Form 7 filer) AGAINST

In the example of Massachusetts, the total contributions, both for and against the candidates, were disproportionately high for two candidates only: Richard R. Tisei, a career Republican politician and John F. Tierney, the incumbent Democratic representative1. 1,674,945 USD and 2,709,485 USD were raised against Tisei and Tierney, respectively. $610,214 were raised for Tisei and 128,229 USD for Tierney. For comparison, the next highest contribution against a candidate was an order of magnitude lower at 15,367 USD and no other candidates in the data set received contribution against them! Why spend over two million dollars against an incumbent democratic congressman from Massachusetts when his main opponent is a Republican? One word explains it all: SCANDAL. Tierneys wife, Patrice was caught in an offshore gambling scandal and this event made him lose credibility. As a result, the Republican party backed Richard Tisei. The decision to fund Tisei congressional seat bid was not without good precedent. This district had gone to Republican Senator Scott Brown by 58% in 20104 . Tisei had also lost the gubernatorial race to another Republican,Charlie Baker by 3,500 votes out of 374,244 cast5, the closest race in New England . In the end, republican efforts were in vain, but only by a slim margin: 47.3% of the vote for Tisei, and 48.3% for Tierney7 .

The 2012 race for representative of 6th Congressional District of Massachusetts is indicative of what often happens in narrow races. A similar pattern happened in 2012 race for Georgias 12th. Close to two million were raised against incumbent John Barrows (Dem) bid. Similarly, over 1.3 million were raised against his main opponent Lee Anderson who ran on an pro-life campaign. The incumbent, Barrows, won 53.70% of the vote but not before giving up 46.30% to Lee8. The 2018 Alabama senate race between Democrat Doug Jones and alleged pedophile and misogynist Republican Roy Moore might reveal a similar monetary campaign spending trend. This was a race where a Democrat won a senate seat for the first time in 5 years. He even had a chance because he was running against Moore, whose past as a sexual harasser was brought up by one of his alleged victims weeks before the election day. This cloud of scandal gave a democrat in the deep south a chance to become a senator. And political animals were likely taking bets.
